04314nam a22006255i 9780226442730DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2017    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264427307 a10.7208/97802264427302doi  a(DE-B1597)523534  a(OCoLC)979416991  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aLIT0000002bisacsh  aNM 90002rvk1 aLegassie, Shayne Aaron, eauthor.14aThe Medieval Invention of Travel /cShayne Aaron Legassie. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b9 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Travail and Travel Writing -- tPart One: Subjectivity, Authority, and the "Exotic" -- t1. Exoticism as the Appropriation of Travail -- t2. Travail and Authority in the Forgotten Age of Discovery -- tPart Two: Pilgrimage as Literate Labor -- t3. Memory Work and the Labor of Writing -- t4. The Pilgrim as Investigator -- tPart Three: Discovering the Proximate -- t5. Becoming Petrarch -- t6. The Chivalric Mediterranean of Pero Tafur -- tCoda: Beyond 1500; or, Travel's Labor's Lost -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the course of the Middle Ages, the economies of Europe, Asia, and northern Africa became more closely integrated, fostering the international and intercontinental journeys of merchants, pilgrims, diplomats, missionaries, and adventurers. During a time in history when travel was often difficult, expensive, and fraught with danger, these wayfarers composed accounts of their experiences in unprecedented numbers and transformed traditional conceptions of human mobility. Exploring this phenomenon, The Medieval Invention of Travel draws on an impressive array of sources to develop original readings of canonical figures such as Marco Polo, John Mandeville, and Petrarch, as well as a host of lesser-known travel writers. As Shayne Aaron Legassie demonstrates, the Middle Ages inherited a Greco-Roman model of heroic travel, which viewed the ideal journey as a triumph over temptation and bodily travail. Medieval travel writers revolutionized this ancient paradigm by incorporating practices of reading and writing into the ascetic regime of the heroic voyager, fashioning a bold new conception of travel that would endure into modern times. Engaging methods and insights from a range of disciplines, The Medieval Invention of Travel offers a comprehensive account of how medieval travel writers and their audiences reshaped the intellectual and material culture of Europe for centuries to come.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aLiterature, MedievalxHistory and criticism. 0aPilgrims and pilgrimages in literature. 0aTravel in literature. 0aTravel writingzEurope, WesternxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aMediterranean Studies. 4aMiddle Ages. 4aethnography. 4aexploration. 4ageography. 4aliteracy. 4apilgrimage. 4atravel writing. 4atravel. 70(DE-601)1041962380(DE-588)4177612-4aReiseliteratur2gnd 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226442730423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226442730.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles